# Phase 2: Background Loading

## Overview

This phase implements the actual snapshot building logic in the BackgroundWorker. Phase 1 gave us the types and plumbing; this phase does the heavy lifting of loading, parsing, and analyzing data entirely off the UI thread.

## Why This Phase Second

Phase 1 established the infrastructure (DataSnapshot, BackgroundWorker, messages). Now we implement the buildSnapshot() method that actually:
1. Reads beads.jsonl from disk
2. Parses JSON lines into Issue structs
3. Runs Phase 1 analysis (graph building, degree, topo sort)
4. Kicks off Phase 2 analysis (async, in yet another goroutine)

## The Core Problem This Solves

Currently in model.go Update() case FileChangedMsg (lines ~1184-1380):
- LoadIssuesFromFileWithOptions() - BLOCKS UI 50-200ms
- NewCachedAnalyzer().AnalyzeAsync() - Phase 1 BLOCKS UI 20-100ms
- Rebuild all view state - BLOCKS UI 50-200ms

After this phase, ALL of that happens in the BackgroundWorker goroutine. The UI thread only does a pointer swap.

## Implementation Details

### buildSnapshot() Method

```go
// buildSnapshot creates a complete DataSnapshot.
// Called from BackgroundWorker goroutine (NOT UI thread).
// This is where all the expensive work happens.
func (w *BackgroundWorker) buildSnapshot() (*DataSnapshot, error) {
    start := time.Now()

    // 1. Load issues from file
    issues, err := loader.LoadIssuesFromFileWithOptions(w.beadsPath, loader.DefaultOptions())
    if err != nil {
        return nil, fmt.Errorf("loading issues: %w", err)
    }

    // 2. Compute content hash for dedup
    hash := computeContentHash(issues)
    if hash == w.lastHash {
        // File changed but content is identical - skip
        return nil, nil
    }
    w.lastHash = hash

    // 3. Build issue map
    issueMap := make(map[string]*model.Issue, len(issues))
    for i := range issues {
        issueMap[issues[i].ID] = &issues[i]
    }

    // 4. Run Phase 1 analysis
    analyzer := analysis.NewAnalyzer(issues)
    stats := analyzer.Analyze() // Phase 1 only, synchronous

    // 5. Kick off Phase 2 (async, will signal when done)
    go w.runPhase2(stats, w.nextVersion.Load())

    // 6. Compute statistics
    var openCount, closedCount, blockedCount, readyCount int
    for _, issue := range issues {
        switch issue.Status {
        case model.StatusOpen:
            openCount++
            if !hasOpenBlockers(issue, issueMap) {
                readyCount++
            }
        case model.StatusClosed:
            closedCount++
        case model.StatusBlocked:
            blockedCount++
        }
    }

    // 7. Build snapshot
    version := w.nextVersion.Add(1)
    snapshot := &DataSnapshot{
        Issues:       issues,
        IssueMap:     issueMap,
        Stats:        stats,
        Phase2Ready:  false, // Will be updated when Phase 2 completes

        Version:      version,
        ContentHash:  hash,
        LoadedAt:     time.Now(),
        SourcePath:   w.beadsPath,

        TotalCount:   len(issues),
        OpenCount:    openCount,
        ClosedCount:  closedCount,
        BlockedCount: blockedCount,
        ReadyCount:   readyCount,

        // View data computed in Phase 3
        ListItems:    nil,
        BoardState:   nil,
        TreeNodes:    nil,
        GraphLayout:  nil,
        InsightsData: nil,
    }

    log.Printf("buildSnapshot: loaded %d issues in %v", len(issues), time.Since(start))
    return snapshot, nil
}

// runPhase2 runs expensive analysis in the background.
// Signals UI when complete via phase2Ch.
func (w *BackgroundWorker) runPhase2(stats *analysis.GraphStats, version uint64) {
    // Phase 2 analysis (PageRank, Betweenness, HITS, etc.)
    stats.ComputePhase2()

    // Signal completion
    select {
    case w.phase2Ch <- Phase2UpdateMsg{Version: version, Stats: stats}:
    default:
        // Channel full, UI will see Phase2Ready on next snapshot
    }
}
```

### Content Hash for Dedup

```go
// computeContentHash creates a hash of the issue content.
// Used to skip redundant processing when file changes but content doesn't.
func computeContentHash(issues []model.Issue) string {
    h := sha256.New()
    for _, issue := range issues {
        // Hash stable fields only (not UpdatedAt which changes on touch)
        fmt.Fprintf(h, "%s|%s|%s|%d|",
            issue.ID,
            issue.Title,
            issue.Status,
            issue.Priority,
        )
    }
    return hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))
}
```

### Helper Function

```go
// hasOpenBlockers checks if an issue has any open blocking dependencies.
func hasOpenBlockers(issue model.Issue, issueMap map[string]*model.Issue) bool {
    for _, dep := range issue.Dependencies {
        if dep.Type == model.DepBlocks || dep.Type == model.DepDependsOn {
            if blocker, exists := issueMap[dep.ID]; exists {
                if blocker.Status == model.StatusOpen || blocker.Status == model.StatusBlocked {
                    return true
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return false
}
```

