# Task: Define DataSnapshot Struct

## Location
Create new file: `pkg/ui/snapshot.go`

## Purpose

DataSnapshot is the central data structure for the background worker architecture. It represents a complete, immutable point-in-time view of all data the UI needs to render any view.

**Key Property: Immutability**
Once a DataSnapshot is created, it MUST NOT be modified. This is what makes thread-safe access possible without locks on the read path.

## Struct Definition

```go
package ui

import (
    "time"
    "github.com/charmbracelet/bubbles/list"
    "github.com/Dicklesworthstone/beads_viewer/pkg/analysis"
    "github.com/Dicklesworthstone/beads_viewer/pkg/model"
)

// DataSnapshot represents an immutable point-in-time view of all data
// needed by the UI. Created by BackgroundWorker, consumed by Model.
//
// IMPORTANT: This struct must remain immutable after creation.
// Never modify fields after the snapshot is sent to the UI.
type DataSnapshot struct {
    // === Core Data ===

    // Issues is the complete list of issues loaded from beads.jsonl.
    // Slice is safe to iterate; backing array is never modified.
    Issues []model.Issue

    // IssueMap provides O(1) lookup by issue ID.
    // Map is safe to read; never written after creation.
    IssueMap map[string]*model.Issue

    // === Analysis Results ===

    // Stats contains Phase 1 analysis results (always populated).
    // Phase 2 fields may be nil/zero until Phase2Ready is true.
    Stats *analysis.GraphStats

    // Phase2Ready indicates whether Phase 2 analysis has completed.
    // UI should check this before accessing PageRank, Betweenness, etc.
    Phase2Ready bool

    // === Pre-computed View Data ===
    // These are ready-to-render structures for each view mode.
    // Computed in background to minimize UI thread work.

    // ListItems is pre-built for the list view.
    // Includes all filtering/sorting already applied based on current recipe.
    ListItems []list.Item

    // BoardState contains pre-computed Kanban board layout.
    // Columns, cards, positions all calculated.
    BoardState *BoardSnapshot

    // TreeNodes contains pre-built hierarchical tree structure.
    // Parent-child relationships resolved, ready for rendering.
    TreeNodes []*TreeNodeSnapshot

    // GraphLayout contains pre-computed graph visualization data.
    // Node positions, edge routing, labels all calculated.
    GraphLayout *GraphSnapshot

    // InsightsData contains pre-computed insights panel data.
    // Top bottlenecks, keystones, cycles, etc.
    InsightsData *InsightsSnapshot

    // === Metadata ===

    // Version is a monotonically increasing counter.
    // Used to detect stale snapshots and order updates.
    Version uint64

    // ContentHash is SHA256 of the source beads.jsonl content.
    // Used to detect if file actually changed (skip redundant processing).
    ContentHash string

    // LoadedAt records when this snapshot was created.
    // Useful for debugging and staleness detection.
    LoadedAt time.Time

    // SourcePath is the path to the beads.jsonl file.
    SourcePath string

    // === Computed Statistics ===
    // Pre-computed counts for status bar and filtering.

    TotalCount   int
    OpenCount    int
    ClosedCount  int
    BlockedCount int
    ReadyCount   int  // Open with no blockers
}

// Sub-snapshot types for each view (define these based on what each view needs)

type BoardSnapshot struct {
    Columns []BoardColumn
    // ... other board-specific pre-computed data
}

type TreeNodeSnapshot struct {
    Issue    *model.Issue
    Children []*TreeNodeSnapshot
    Depth    int
    Expanded bool
}

type GraphSnapshot struct {
    Nodes []GraphNode
    Edges []GraphEdge
    // ... layout data
}

type InsightsSnapshot struct {
    Bottlenecks []RankedItem
    Keystones   []RankedItem
    Influencers []RankedItem
    Hubs        []RankedItem
    Authorities []RankedItem
    Cycles      [][]string
    // ... other pre-computed insights
}

type RankedItem struct {
    ID    string
    Title string
    Score float64
}
```

## Design Rationale

### Why include pre-computed view data?
Without pre-computation, the UI thread must transform raw Issues into renderable structures on every frame. This transformation can take 50-100ms for large datasets. By pre-computing in the background, rendering becomes O(visible items) instead of O(all items).

### Why store both Issues slice and IssueMap?
- Slice: Needed for ordered iteration (list view, exports)
- Map: Needed for O(1) lookup (dependency resolution, selection)
- Both reference the same underlying Issue objects (no duplication)

### Why track Version?
When switching between snapshots rapidly, Version ensures we never accidentally apply an older snapshot over a newer one. The UI can compare versions before accepting an update.

### Why track ContentHash?
If agents write to the file but the content is identical (e.g., reformatting), we can skip the expensive rebuild entirely. Hash comparison is O(1) after initial computation.

