# Task: Implement Idle-time GC Triggering

## Location
Add to: `pkg/ui/background_worker.go`

## Purpose

Go's GC runs automatically when the heap grows. Under heavy snapshot creation, GC may trigger during user interaction, causing visible stutters. By proactively triggering GC during idle periods, we can:
1. Reduce surprise GC pauses during interaction
2. Keep heap size smaller (less work for GC when it does run)
3. Make GC timing predictable

## The Problem

```
Timeline with automatic GC:
в”ңв”Җ 0ms:    User presses 'j' (navigate down)
в”ңв”Җ 1ms:    Update() starts processing
в”ңв”Җ 2ms:    GC TRIGGERS (heap threshold reached)
в”ңв”Җ 12ms:   GC completes (10ms pause!)
в”ңв”Җ 13ms:   Update() resumes
в”ңв”Җ 14ms:   View() renders
в””в”Җ User perceives 14ms latency (should be 3ms)
```

## The Solution

```
Timeline with idle-time GC:
в”ңв”Җ 0ms:    Last snapshot delivered
в”ңв”Җ ...
в”ңв”Җ 5000ms: Still idle, trigger GC
в”ңв”Җ 5010ms: GC completes (user not interacting, no impact)
в”ңв”Җ ...
в”ңв”Җ 8000ms: User presses 'j'
в”ңв”Җ 8001ms: Update() processes
в”ңв”Җ 8002ms: View() renders (heap is small, no GC needed)
в””в”Җ User perceives 2ms latency
```

## Implementation

```go
// In background_worker.go

type BackgroundWorker struct {
    // ... existing fields ...

    // Idle-time GC management
    lastActivityTime atomic.Value // time.Time
    gcTicker         *time.Ticker
    gcStop           chan struct{}
}

// Start includes idle GC goroutine
func (w *BackgroundWorker) Start() error {
    // ... existing start code ...

    // Start idle GC checker
    w.gcTicker = time.NewTicker(10 * time.Second)
    w.gcStop = make(chan struct{})
    w.lastActivityTime.Store(time.Now())

    w.wg.Add(1)
    go w.idleGCLoop()

    return nil
}

// Stop includes cleanup
func (w *BackgroundWorker) Stop() {
    // ... existing stop code ...

    if w.gcTicker != nil {
        w.gcTicker.Stop()
        close(w.gcStop)
    }
}

// idleGCLoop periodically checks for idle periods and triggers GC
func (w *BackgroundWorker) idleGCLoop() {
    defer w.wg.Done()

    for {
        select {
        case <-w.gcStop:
            return

        case <-w.gcTicker.C:
            w.maybeIdleGC()
        }
    }
}

// maybeIdleGC triggers GC if we've been idle long enough
func (w *BackgroundWorker) maybeIdleGC() {
    lastActivity := w.lastActivityTime.Load().(time.Time)
    idleDuration := time.Since(lastActivity)

    // Only GC if idle for at least 5 seconds
    // and not currently processing
    w.mu.Lock()
    processing := w.processing
    w.mu.Unlock()

    if !processing && idleDuration > 5*time.Second {
        start := time.Now()
        runtime.GC()
        gcDuration := time.Since(start)

        if gcDuration > 5*time.Millisecond {
            log.Printf("idle GC completed in %v", gcDuration)
        }
    }
}

// recordActivity should be called when work happens
func (w *BackgroundWorker) recordActivity() {
    w.lastActivityTime.Store(time.Now())
}

// Called when snapshot is built
func (w *BackgroundWorker) buildSnapshot() (*DataSnapshot, error) {
    w.recordActivity()
    // ... existing code ...
}
```

## UI Integration

The UI should also record activity on user input:

```go
// In model.go Update()
func (m Model) Update(msg tea.Msg) (tea.Model, tea.Cmd) {
    // Record activity for any user input
    switch msg.(type) {
    case tea.KeyMsg, tea.MouseMsg:
        if m.backgroundWorker != nil {
            m.backgroundWorker.recordActivity()
        }
    }

    // ... existing handlers ...
}
```

## Configuration

Make thresholds configurable:

```go
const (
    // How long to wait before triggering idle GC
    defaultIdleGCThreshold = 5 * time.Second

    // How often to check for idle state
    defaultIdleGCCheckInterval = 10 * time.Second
)

type GCConfig struct {
    IdleThreshold time.Duration
    CheckInterval time.Duration
    Enabled       bool
}

func (w *BackgroundWorker) SetGCConfig(cfg GCConfig) {
    // Update ticker interval if needed
    // ...
}
```

## GOGC Tuning

Combine with GOGC tuning for best results:

```go
// In main.go or init
func init() {
    // Higher GOGC = less automatic GC, rely more on idle GC
    debug.SetGCPercent(200)
}
```

Rationale for GOGC=200:
- Default GOGC=100: GC when heap doubles
- GOGC=200: GC when heap triples
- This means automatic GC is less likely to trigger during interaction
- Idle GC handles cleanup during quiet periods
- Trade-off: higher peak memory usage, but smoother UX

## Monitoring

Add metrics to track effectiveness:

```go
var (
    idleGCCount    uint64 // atomic
    idleGCTotalMs  uint64 // atomic
    autoGCCount    uint64 // From runtime/metrics
)

func (w *BackgroundWorker) maybeIdleGC() {
    // ... check conditions ...

    start := time.Now()
    runtime.GC()
    duration := time.Since(start)

    atomic.AddUint64(&idleGCCount, 1)
    atomic.AddUint64(&idleGCTotalMs, uint64(duration.Milliseconds()))
}
```

## Testing

```go
func TestIdleGCTriggersAfterThreshold(t *testing.T) {
    w := NewBackgroundWorker(...)
    w.Start()

    // Wait for idle GC to trigger
    time.Sleep(6 * time.Second)

    // Verify GC ran (check metrics or memory stats)
}

func TestIdleGCDoesNotTriggerDuringActivity(t *testing.T) {
    w := NewBackgroundWorker(...)
    w.Start()

    // Keep recording activity
    done := make(chan struct{})
    go func() {
        for {
            select {
            case <-done:
                return
            default:
                w.recordActivity()
                time.Sleep(100 * time.Millisecond)
            }
        }
    }()

    // Wait and verify no idle GC
    time.Sleep(6 * time.Second)
    close(done)

    // Check no idle GC was triggered
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Idle GC loop running in background
- [ ] GC triggered after 5 seconds of inactivity
- [ ] GC NOT triggered during active processing
- [ ] User input recorded as activity
- [ ] GOGC set to 200 (or documented alternative)
- [ ] Metrics available for monitoring
- [ ] No impact on responsiveness during interaction

# Task: Implement sync.Pool for Issue Struct Reuse

## Location
Add to: `pkg/loader/pool.go` (new file)
Modify: `pkg/loader/loader.go`

## Purpose

Under heavy load, we create many Issue structs rapidly. Each struct allocates:
- The struct itself (~200 bytes)
- Dependencies slice header + backing array
- Comments slice header + backing array
- Labels slice header + backing array
- Various strings

By pooling Issue structs, we can reuse allocations and reduce GC pressure.

## Implementation

```go
// pkg/loader/pool.go
package loader

import (
    "sync"
    "github.com/Dicklesworthstone/beads_viewer/pkg/model"
)

// IssuePool manages reusable Issue structs.
// Using sync.Pool provides automatic cleanup under memory pressure.
var IssuePool = sync.Pool{
    New: func() any {
        return &model.Issue{
            // Pre-allocate slices with typical capacity
            // These won't be garbage collected when issue is returned
            Dependencies: make([]*model.Dependency, 0, 8),
            Comments:     make([]*model.Comment, 0, 4),
            Labels:       make([]string, 0, 8),
        }
    },
}

// GetIssue retrieves an Issue from the pool.
// The returned issue has zeroed fields but preserved slice capacity.
func GetIssue() *model.Issue {
    issue := IssuePool.Get().(*model.Issue)

    // Reset to zero state while preserving slice capacity
    resetIssue(issue)

    return issue
}

// PutIssue returns an Issue to the pool for reuse.
// After this call, the issue must not be used.
func PutIssue(issue *model.Issue) {
    if issue == nil {
        return
    }

    // Clear references to allow GC of pointed-to objects
    // but keep slice capacity
    clearIssueReferences(issue)

    IssuePool.Put(issue)
}

// resetIssue zeroes all fields while preserving slice capacity.
func resetIssue(issue *model.Issue) {
    // Preserve slice capacity by slicing to zero length
    deps := issue.Dependencies[:0]
    comments := issue.Comments[:0]
    labels := issue.Labels[:0]

    // Zero all fields
    *issue = model.Issue{}

    // Restore slices with preserved capacity
    issue.Dependencies = deps
    issue.Comments = comments
    issue.Labels = labels
}

// clearIssueReferences nils out pointers to allow GC.
func clearIssueReferences(issue *model.Issue) {
    // Clear dependency pointers
    for i := range issue.Dependencies {
        issue.Dependencies[i] = nil
    }
    issue.Dependencies = issue.Dependencies[:0]

    // Clear comment pointers
    for i := range issue.Comments {
        issue.Comments[i] = nil
    }
    issue.Comments = issue.Comments[:0]

    // Clear labels (strings are immutable, clearing slice is enough)
    issue.Labels = issue.Labels[:0]

    // Clear other pointer fields
    issue.DueDate = nil
    issue.ClosedAt = nil
    issue.EstimatedMinutes = nil
    issue.ExternalRef = nil
}

// ReturnIssuesToPool returns a slice of issues to the pool.
// Useful when replacing a snapshot.
func ReturnIssuesToPool(issues []model.Issue) {
    for i := range issues {
        PutIssue(&issues[i])
    }
}
```

## Integration with Loader

```go
// In pkg/loader/loader.go

func ParseIssues(r io.Reader) ([]model.Issue, error) {
    // ... existing setup ...

    var issues []model.Issue

    for scanner.Scan() {
        line := scanner.Bytes()

        // Get issue from pool
        issue := GetIssue()

        if err := json.Unmarshal(line, issue); err != nil {
            // Return to pool on error
            PutIssue(issue)
            continue // or return error
        }

        issues = append(issues, *issue)

        // Note: We copy the issue, so we can return the pointer
        // Actually, let's think about this more carefully...
    }

    return issues, nil
}
```

## Important Consideration: Value vs Pointer

The current design uses `[]model.Issue` (values), not `[]*model.Issue` (pointers).

With values, we need to copy from the pool:
```go
poolIssue := GetIssue()
json.Unmarshal(line, poolIssue)
issues = append(issues, *poolIssue) // COPY
PutIssue(poolIssue)  // Return original to pool
```

This still helps because:
1. We reuse the slice backing arrays (Dependencies, Comments, Labels)
2. The copy is fast (just copying struct fields, not allocating)
3. The pool object can be reused for the next line

Alternative with pointers (`[]*model.Issue`):
```go
poolIssue := GetIssue()
json.Unmarshal(line, poolIssue)
issues = append(issues, poolIssue) // No copy, use pool object directly
// Don't return to pool - snapshot now owns it
```

This is more efficient but requires changing the data model. Consider for Phase 5.

## Integration with Background Worker

```go
// When replacing a snapshot, return old issues to pool
func (m *Model) handleSnapshotReady(msg SnapshotReadyMsg) {
    old := m.snapshot
    m.snapshot = msg.Snapshot

    // Return old issues to pool asynchronously
    // (Don't block UI thread)
    if old != nil {
        go ReturnIssuesToPool(old.Issues)
    }
}
```

## Testing

```go
func TestIssuePoolBasic(t *testing.T) {
    issue := GetIssue()
    require.NotNil(t, issue)
    require.Empty(t, issue.ID)

    issue.ID = "test-123"
    PutIssue(issue)

    // Get again - might be same object
    issue2 := GetIssue()
    require.Empty(t, issue2.ID) // Should be reset
}

func TestIssuePoolSliceCapacity(t *testing.T) {
    issue := GetIssue()

    // Add some dependencies
    for i := 0; i < 5; i++ {
        issue.Dependencies = append(issue.Dependencies, &model.Dependency{})
    }

    PutIssue(issue)

    issue2 := GetIssue()
    require.Empty(t, issue2.Dependencies)
    require.GreaterOrEqual(t, cap(issue2.Dependencies), 5)
}

func BenchmarkWithPool(b *testing.B) {
    b.ReportAllocs()
    for i := 0; i < b.N; i++ {
        issue := GetIssue()
        issue.ID = "test"
        PutIssue(issue)
    }
}

func BenchmarkWithoutPool(b *testing.B) {
    b.ReportAllocs()
    for i := 0; i < b.N; i++ {
        issue := &model.Issue{}
        issue.ID = "test"
        // Becomes garbage
    }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] sync.Pool created for Issue structs
- [ ] GetIssue() returns reset issue with preserved slice capacity
- [ ] PutIssue() clears references and returns to pool
- [ ] Loader uses pool for parsing
- [ ] Old snapshot issues returned to pool
- [ ] Benchmark shows reduced allocations
- [ ] No data races (verified with -race flag)

# Phase 4: GC Optimizations

## Overview

When the background worker creates snapshots rapidly (2-3 per second under heavy agent load), we generate significant garbage:
- Old snapshots become unreachable
- Each snapshot allocates ~2-5MB for 1000 issues
- GC must run frequently to reclaim memory
- GC pauses can cause UI stutters

This phase implements optimizations to reduce GC pressure.

## Why This Matters

Even with background processing, GC runs on ALL goroutines (including UI). A long GC pause (10-50ms) can cause visible stuttering. The goal is:
1. Reduce allocation rate (less garbage to collect)
2. Reduce live set size (faster GC when it runs)
3. Time GC to happen during idle periods (not during interaction)

## Optimization Strategies

### 1. Object Pooling with sync.Pool

Reuse Issue structs instead of allocating new ones:

```go
var issuePool = sync.Pool{
    New: func() any {
        return &model.Issue{
            Dependencies: make([]*model.Dependency, 0, 8),
            Comments:     make([]*model.Comment, 0, 4),
            Labels:       make([]string, 0, 4),
        }
    },
}

// In loader
func parseIssue(data []byte) (*model.Issue, error) {
    issue := issuePool.Get().(*model.Issue)

    // Reset fields (keep allocated slices)
    *issue = model.Issue{
        Dependencies: issue.Dependencies[:0],
        Comments:     issue.Comments[:0],
        Labels:       issue.Labels[:0],
    }

    if err := json.Unmarshal(data, issue); err != nil {
        issuePool.Put(issue) // Return on error
        return nil, err
    }

    return issue, nil
}

// When snapshot is replaced
func returnSnapshotToPool(old *DataSnapshot) {
    if old == nil {
        return
    }
    for i := range old.Issues {
        issuePool.Put(&old.Issues[i])
    }
}
```

### 2. Slice Capacity Reuse

Avoid slice growth during loading:

```go
// BAD: grows slice repeatedly
issues := make([]model.Issue, 0)
for line := range lines {
    issues = append(issues, parseIssue(line))
}

// GOOD: pre-allocate based on file size estimate
estimatedCount := fileSize / avgIssueSize
issues := make([]model.Issue, 0, estimatedCount)
for line := range lines {
    issues = append(issues, parseIssue(line))
}
```

### 3. Map Pre-sizing

Avoid map rehashing:

```go
// BAD: map grows and rehashes
issueMap := make(map[string]*model.Issue)

// GOOD: pre-sized to avoid growth
issueMap := make(map[string]*model.Issue, len(issues))
```

### 4. GOGC Tuning

Adjust GC frequency for this workload:

```go
// In main() or init()
import "runtime/debug"

func init() {
    // Default GOGC=100 means GC when heap doubles
    // Higher = less frequent GC, more memory
    // For bv, we prefer fewer GC pauses over memory
    debug.SetGCPercent(200)  // GC when heap triples
}
```

### 5. Idle-time GC

Trigger GC during quiet periods:

```go
// In background worker
func (w *BackgroundWorker) maybeGC() {
    w.mu.Lock()
    idle := !w.processing && time.Since(w.lastSnapshotTime) > 5*time.Second
    w.mu.Unlock()

    if idle {
        // Force GC during idle, not during interaction
        runtime.GC()
    }
}

// Run periodically
go func() {
    ticker := time.NewTicker(10 * time.Second)
    for range ticker.C {
        w.maybeGC()
    }
}()
```

### 6. String Interning for Repeated Values

Many issues share the same labels, assignees, etc.:

```go
var stringIntern sync.Map

func internString(s string) string {
    if v, ok := stringIntern.Load(s); ok {
        return v.(string)
    }
    stringIntern.Store(s, s)
    return s
}

// In loader
issue.Assignee = internString(issue.Assignee)
for i, label := range issue.Labels {
    issue.Labels[i] = internString(label)
}
```

