# Port K-Shortest Paths and Parallel Cut

## Context
K-Shortest Paths finds multiple critical paths through the graph. Parallel Cut analyzes opportunities for parallel work.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// KPathsResult, ParallelCutResult in advanced_insights.go
```

## Rust Implementation

### advanced/k_paths.rs
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;
use crate::algorithms::topo::topological_sort;

pub struct CriticalPath {
    pub nodes: Vec<usize>,
    pub length: usize,
}

/// Find k longest paths in DAG.
pub fn k_critical_paths(graph: &DiGraph, k: usize) -> Vec<CriticalPath> {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    if n == 0 { return Vec::new(); }

    let order = match topological_sort(graph) {
        Some(o) => o,
        None => return Vec::new(),
    };

    // Compute distances and track predecessors
    let mut dist = vec![0usize; n];
    let mut pred = vec![None; n];

    for &v in &order {
        for &u in graph.predecessors(v) {
            if dist[u] + 1 > dist[v] {
                dist[v] = dist[u] + 1;
                pred[v] = Some(u);
            }
        }
    }

    // Find k sinks with longest paths
    let mut sinks: Vec<(usize, usize)> = (0..n)
        .filter(|&v| graph.out_degree(v) == 0 || dist[v] > 0)
        .map(|v| (v, dist[v]))
        .collect();
    sinks.sort_by(|a, b| b.1.cmp(&a.1));
    sinks.truncate(k);

    // Reconstruct paths
    sinks.iter().map(|&(sink, len)| {
        let mut path = vec![sink];
        let mut curr = sink;
        while let Some(p) = pred[curr] {
            path.push(p);
            curr = p;
        }
        path.reverse();
        CriticalPath { nodes: path, length: len + 1 }
    }).collect()
}
```

### advanced/parallel_cut.rs
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;

pub struct ParallelCutItem {
    pub node: usize,
    pub parallel_gain: i32,
}

/// Find issues that increase parallelization when completed.
pub fn parallel_cut_suggestions(graph: &DiGraph, closed_set: &[bool], limit: usize) -> Vec<ParallelCutItem> {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    let mut suggestions: Vec<ParallelCutItem> = (0..n)
        .filter(|&v| !closed_set.get(v).copied().unwrap_or(false))
        .map(|v| {
            // Count how many dependents become actionable
            let gain = graph.successors(v).iter()
                .filter(|&&w| {
                    !closed_set.get(w).copied().unwrap_or(false) &&
                    graph.predecessors(w).iter()
                        .filter(|&&p| p != v)
                        .all(|&p| closed_set.get(p).copied().unwrap_or(false))
                })
                .count();
            ParallelCutItem { node: v, parallel_gain: gain as i32 - 1 }
        })
        .filter(|item| item.parallel_gain > 0)
        .collect();

    suggestions.sort_by(|a, b| b.parallel_gain.cmp(&a.parallel_gain));
    suggestions.truncate(limit);
    suggestions
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] K paths returned in length order
- [ ] Parallel cut identifies bottleneck removals
- [ ] Results match Go advanced_insights

# Port Cycle Break Suggestions

## Context
Cycle Break analyzes which edges to remove to break cycles with minimal collateral damage.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// generateCycleBreakSuggestions in advanced_insights.go
```

## Rust Implementation (advanced/cycle_break.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;
use crate::algorithms::cycles::tarjan_scc;

pub struct CycleBreakItem {
    pub from: usize,
    pub to: usize,
    pub cycles_broken: usize,
    pub collateral: usize,
}

/// Suggest edges to remove for breaking cycles.
pub fn cycle_break_suggestions(graph: &DiGraph, limit: usize) -> Vec<CycleBreakItem> {
    let scc = tarjan_scc(graph);
    if !scc.has_cycles {
        return Vec::new();
    }

    let mut suggestions = Vec::new();

    // For each SCC with >1 node, find edges within it
    for component in &scc.components {
        if component.len() <= 1 { continue; }

        let comp_set: std::collections::HashSet<usize> = component.iter().copied().collect();

        for &from in component {
            for &to in graph.successors(from) {
                if comp_set.contains(&to) {
                    // This edge is within a cycle
                    let collateral = graph.successors(from).len() + graph.predecessors(to).len();

                    suggestions.push(CycleBreakItem {
                        from,
                        to,
                        cycles_broken: 1, // Simplified: assume breaks 1 cycle
                        collateral,
                    });
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // Sort by collateral (ascending) - prefer minimal impact
    suggestions.sort_by(|a, b| a.collateral.cmp(&b.collateral));
    suggestions.truncate(limit);
    suggestions
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Only suggests edges within cycles
- [ ] Collateral damage computed
- [ ] Sorted by minimal impact

# Port Coverage Set (Vertex Cover)

## Context
Coverage set finds a minimal set of nodes that "covers" all edges - useful for understanding which issues touch the most dependency relationships.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// generateCoverageSet in advanced_insights.go
// Greedy 2-approximation vertex cover
```

## Rust Implementation (advanced/coverage.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;

pub struct CoverageItem {
    pub node: usize,
    pub edges_added: usize,
}

pub struct CoverageResult {
    pub items: Vec<CoverageItem>,
    pub edges_covered: usize,
    pub total_edges: usize,
}

/// Greedy vertex cover - 2-approximation algorithm.
pub fn coverage_set(graph: &DiGraph, limit: usize) -> CoverageResult {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    let total_edges = graph.edge_count();

    // Track covered edges
    let mut covered = vec![vec![false; n]; n];
    let mut edges_covered = 0;
    let mut selected = Vec::new();

    for _ in 0..limit {
        // Find node covering most uncovered edges
        let mut best_node = None;
        let mut best_count = 0;

        for v in 0..n {
            let mut count = 0;
            // Count uncovered outgoing edges
            for &w in graph.successors(v) {
                if !covered[v][w] { count += 1; }
            }
            // Count uncovered incoming edges
            for &u in graph.predecessors(v) {
                if !covered[u][v] { count += 1; }
            }

            if count > best_count {
                best_count = count;
                best_node = Some(v);
            }
        }

        match best_node {
            Some(node) if best_count > 0 => {
                // Mark edges as covered
                for &w in graph.successors(node) {
                    covered[node][w] = true;
                }
                for &u in graph.predecessors(node) {
                    covered[u][node] = true;
                }

                selected.push(CoverageItem {
                    node,
                    edges_added: best_count,
                });
                edges_covered += best_count;
            }
            _ => break,
        }
    }

    CoverageResult {
        items: selected,
        edges_covered,
        total_edges,
    }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Greedy covers edges efficiently
- [ ] Returns coverage ratio
- [ ] Respects limit parameter

