# Temporal Correlation

## Context
When a bead was "in progress" from T1 to T2 by author "bob@dev", commits by bob@dev between T1 and T2 are LIKELY related to that bead.

This is lower confidence (40-70%) because:
- Bob might have multiple beads in progress
- The commit might be unrelated refactoring

But it's still useful as a fallback when other methods don't apply.

## Algorithm
1. Find bead's claimed timestamp (T1) and closed timestamp (T2)
2. Find all commits by the claiming author between T1 and T2
3. Filter out commits already correlated via higher-confidence methods
4. Calculate dynamic confidence based on context

## Dynamic Confidence Calculation
\`\`\`go
func calculateTemporalConfidence(bead, commit, context) float64 {
    base := 0.50

    // Factor 1: How many beads was this author working on?
    if activeBeads == 1 {
        base += 0.20  // Only one bead = higher confidence
    } else if activeBeads > 3 {
        base -= 0.10  // Many beads = lower confidence
    }

    // Factor 2: How long is the time window?
    if window < 4*time.Hour {
        base += 0.10  // Short window = more focused
    } else if window > 7*24*time.Hour {
        base -= 0.15  // Week+ window = lots of potential commits
    }

    // Factor 3: Does commit touch files related to bead?
    if pathsMatchBeadHints(commit.Files, bead.Title) {
        base += 0.15  // File paths match keywords in title
    }

    return clamp(base, 0.20, 0.85)
}
\`\`\`

## Path Hint Extraction
Extract potential file paths from bead title/description:
- File paths: path/to/file.go
- Package names: pkg/auth, src/components
- Keywords: auth, login, user, api, db, config

## File Location
\`pkg/correlation/temporal.go\`

## Acceptance Criteria
1. Finds commits within bead's active window
2. Matches by author/email
3. Dynamic confidence based on context
4. Extracts and uses path hints
5. Never overwrites higher-confidence correlations

# Phase 5: Incremental Updates (Future Enhancement)

## Overview

Phases 1-4 make the UI responsive by moving ALL work to the background. But we still do a FULL rebuild on every file change, even if only one issue was modified.

Phase 5 adds incremental updates: detect what changed, rebuild only affected parts.

## Why This Is Phase 5 (Future)

This phase is:
- More complex to implement correctly
- Has diminishing returns (Phases 1-4 solve 90% of the problem)
- Requires careful cache invalidation logic
- Should only be attempted after Phases 1-4 are stable

## The Opportunity

With Phases 1-4, a typical rebuild takes:
- Load: 50-200ms (but in background, no UI impact)
- Analysis: 50-200ms (but in background)
- View pre-computation: 50-100ms (but in background)

With incremental updates:
- Detect changed issues: ~5ms
- Update only affected: ~10-50ms
- Skip unchanged: 0ms

For scenarios where one agent modifies one issue, this could reduce background work from 200ms to 20ms.

## How It Would Work

### 1. Issue-level Change Detection

```go
type IssueFingerprint struct {
    ID           string
    ContentHash  string  // Hash of title, description, status, etc.
    DependencyHash string // Hash of dependency IDs
}

func computeFingerprint(issue *model.Issue) IssueFingerprint {
    h := sha256.New()
    fmt.Fprintf(h, "%s|%s|%s|%d|", issue.ID, issue.Title, issue.Status, issue.Priority)
    contentHash := hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))[:16]

    h.Reset()
    for _, dep := range issue.Dependencies {
        fmt.Fprintf(h, "%s|", dep.ID)
    }
    depHash := hex.EncodeToString(h.Sum(nil))[:16]

    return IssueFingerprint{
        ID:            issue.ID,
        ContentHash:   contentHash,
        DependencyHash: depHash,
    }
}
```

### 2. Diff Detection

```go
type IssueDiff struct {
    Added    []string  // New issue IDs
    Removed  []string  // Deleted issue IDs
    Modified []string  // Changed issue IDs (content or deps)
    Unchanged []string // Same as before
}

func computeDiff(old, new []model.Issue) IssueDiff {
    oldFP := make(map[string]IssueFingerprint)
    for _, issue := range old {
        oldFP[issue.ID] = computeFingerprint(&issue)
    }

    newFP := make(map[string]IssueFingerprint)
    for _, issue := range new {
        newFP[issue.ID] = computeFingerprint(&issue)
    }

    var diff IssueDiff

    // Find added and modified
    for id, newF := range newFP {
        oldF, exists := oldFP[id]
        if !exists {
            diff.Added = append(diff.Added, id)
        } else if oldF.ContentHash != newF.ContentHash || oldF.DependencyHash != newF.DependencyHash {
            diff.Modified = append(diff.Modified, id)
        } else {
            diff.Unchanged = append(diff.Unchanged, id)
        }
    }

    // Find removed
    for id := range oldFP {
        if _, exists := newFP[id]; !exists {
            diff.Removed = append(diff.Removed, id)
        }
    }

    return diff
}
```

### 3. Incremental Graph Update

```go
func (stats *GraphStats) IncrementalUpdate(diff IssueDiff, newIssues map[string]*model.Issue) {
    // If any dependency changed, need to rebuild graph structure
    if len(diff.Added) > 0 || len(diff.Removed) > 0 || anyDepsChanged(diff, newIssues) {
        // Full graph rebuild needed
        stats.rebuildGraph(newIssues)
        return
    }

    // Only content changed - update node properties, not edges
    for _, id := range diff.Modified {
        issue := newIssues[id]
        stats.updateNodeProperties(id, issue)
    }
}

