### 4. Incremental View Update

```go
// For list view
func (w *BackgroundWorker) incrementalListUpdate(
    oldItems []list.Item,
    diff IssueDiff,
    newIssueMap map[string]*model.Issue,
) []list.Item {
    // If sorted by something other than ID, full rebuild needed
    // (position might change even for unchanged items)

    // For ID-based position:
    items := make([]list.Item, 0, len(newIssueMap))

    for _, item := range oldItems {
        issueItem := item.(IssueListItem)
        if contains(diff.Unchanged, issueItem.ID) {
            // Reuse existing item
            items = append(items, item)
        } else if contains(diff.Modified, issueItem.ID) {
            // Rebuild this item
            newItem := buildListItem(newIssueMap[issueItem.ID])
            items = append(items, newItem)
        }
        // Removed items: skip
    }

    // Add new items
    for _, id := range diff.Added {
        items = append(items, buildListItem(newIssueMap[id]))
    }

    return items
}
```

### 5. Cascade Invalidation

When an issue changes, what else is affected?

```
Issue A modified вҶ’ Rebuild A's list item
                вҶ’ If A's deps changed вҶ’ Rebuild graph
                вҶ’ Rebuild any issue that depends on A
                вҶ’ Rebuild board (A might move columns)
                вҶ’ Rebuild tree (parent-child might change)
                вҶ’ Rebuild insights (metrics might change)
```

This cascade is why incremental updates are complex - one change can invalidate many things.

### 6. Decision Tree

```go
func (w *BackgroundWorker) buildSnapshotIncremental() (*DataSnapshot, error) {
    // Load new issues
    newIssues, err := loader.LoadIssues(w.beadsPath)

    // Get old snapshot
    oldSnapshot := w.lastSnapshot
    if oldSnapshot == nil {
        // No previous snapshot - full build
        return w.buildSnapshotFull(newIssues)
    }

    // Compute diff
    diff := computeDiff(oldSnapshot.Issues, newIssues)

    // Decide: incremental or full?
    if shouldDoFullRebuild(diff) {
        return w.buildSnapshotFull(newIssues)
    }

    // Incremental build
    return w.applyIncremental(oldSnapshot, diff, newIssues)
}

func shouldDoFullRebuild(diff IssueDiff) bool {
    // Full rebuild if too many changes
    changeCount := len(diff.Added) + len(diff.Removed) + len(diff.Modified)
    totalCount := changeCount + len(diff.Unchanged)

    // If more than 20% changed, just do full rebuild
    // Incremental has overhead; not worth it for large changes
    if totalCount > 0 && float64(changeCount)/float64(totalCount) > 0.2 {
        return true
    }

    // Full rebuild if deps changed (graph structure affected)
    // This needs more sophisticated detection

    return false
}
```

## Why This Is Hard

1. **Cache Invalidation**: Must correctly identify all transitive effects of a change
2. **Correctness**: Incremental must produce identical results to full rebuild
3. **Complexity vs Benefit**: Marginal benefit for significant complexity
4. **Testing**: Need to verify incremental == full for all cases

## Recommended Approach

If implementing Phase 5:
1. Start with diff detection only (no incremental rebuild yet)
2. Add metrics to measure what % of changes are small
3. Implement incremental for list view first (simplest)
4. Add incremental for other views one at a time
5. Always have fallback to full rebuild

